{{For|other people of the same name|Tom Williams (disambiguation){{!}}Tom Williams}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox rugby biography | name = Tom Williams | image = Tom Williams 2013 (cropped).jpg | caption = Williams in 2013 | birth_name = Thomas Williams | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|10|12}} | birth_place = [[Brighton]], England | height = {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|abbr=on}} | weight = {{convert|91|kg|stlb|abbr=on}} <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.union.quins.co.uk/rugby/1stXV.php?player=5038&includeref=dynamic |title=Harlequins 1st XV |year=2011 |work=web page |publisher=Harlequins |accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref> | nickname = | school = | university = | relatives = | ru_position = [[Wing (rugby union)|Wing]] / [[Fullback (rugby union)|Full-back]] | ru_currentteam = | ru_youthyears = | ru_youthclubs = | ru_clubyears = 2004–15 | ru_proclubs = [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] | ru_clubcaps = 208 | ru_clubpoints = (304) | ru_nationalyears = | ru_nationalteam = | ru_nationalcaps = | ru_nationalpoints = | ru_sevensnationalyears = 2004– | ru_sevensnationalteam = [[England national rugby sevens team|England]] | ru_sevensnationalcomp = [[Hong Kong Sevens|Hong Kong]] | pcupdate = | repupdate = }}
'''Tom Williams''' (born 12 October 1983) is an [[English people|English]] former [[rugby union]] player who played for [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]] in the [[Aviva Premiership]]. He normally played at either [[Fullback (rugby union)|full-back]] or on the [[Wing (rugby union)|wing]].
Williams represented Wales at U16 and U19 level, then switched to England for the 2002 IRB U19 World Cup.<ref name="‘Welshman’ Williams waits for ‘Bloodgate’ decision">{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/rugbynation/rugby-news/2009/08/17/welshman-williams-waits-for-bloodgate-decision-91466-24455287/|title=‘Welshman’ Williams waits for ‘Bloodgate’ decision|publisher=Wales Online|date=2009-08-17|accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref>
Williams represented [[England national rugby sevens team|England]] in the [[2003-04 World Sevens Series]],<ref name="Williams gets sevens call">{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/52869.html|title=Williams gets sevens call|publisher=ESPN Scrum|date=2004-03-24|accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> winning the [[Hong Kong Sevens|Hong Kong leg]].<ref name="ESPN Scrum Profile">{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/52869.html|title=ESPN Scrum profile|publisher=ESPN Scrum|date=2009-09-24|accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> He also competed in the [[2006-07 IRB Sevens World Series]].<ref name="Disappointment for England as they bow out of Hong Kong">{{cite web|url=http://www.rfu.com/News/2007/April/News%20Articles/DisappointmentForEnglandAsTheyBowOutOfHongKong?a=1&y=2007|title=Disappointment for England as they bow out of Hong Kong|publisher=RFU|date=2007-04-01|accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref>
He started and scored a try for Harlequins in their [[2011–12 English Premiership (rugby union)|2011–12 Premiership]] final victory over [[Leicester Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/18154802|title=Harlequins 30-23 Leicester|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref> He is a member of the “200 Club” having represented Harlequins for over 200 1st games.
==Bloodgate== {{main article|Bloodgate}} During the [[2008–09 Heineken Cup#Quarter-finals|2008–09 Heineken Cup quarter final]] against [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]], Williams was told to fake a blood injury by Dean Richards to allow a tactical substitition to reintroduce [[Nick Evans (rugby union)|Nick Evans]] leading to the bloodgate scandal. This resulted in a 12-month ban for Williams, (reduced to four months on appeal), a three-year ban for former director of rugby [[Dean Richards (rugby union)|Dean Richards]] as well as a two-year ban for physiotherapist Steph Brennan from the [[European Rugby Cup|ERC]] with a £260,000 fine for the club.<ref name="Quins escape further action in bloodgate scandal">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jSXi8yJtwOWzH4F4Fd2ClRfW1-jA|title=Quins escape further action in bloodgate scandal|publisher=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]|date=2009-08-24|accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref> Tom remains the only one to apologise for this scandal.
